WEBVTT

00:01.084 --> 00:02.293
FEMALE NARRATOR:
<i>Previously on </i>Boston Legal...

00:02.377 --> 00:04.129
Aren't women just the best?

00:04.212 --> 00:07.507
You've been through wives before, Denny.
Five of them.

00:07.590 --> 00:08.925
-Bella.
-Beverly Bridge.

00:09.009 --> 00:10.218
-Bethany.
-Clovis.

00:10.301 --> 00:12.095
-She's the one.
-She's the one.

00:12.178 --> 00:15.557
After five or six wives,
you still believe in the one?

00:15.640 --> 00:17.809
-Denny, you're glowing.
-She's an amazing woman, Alan.

00:17.892 --> 00:19.436
Mad cow. Mad cow. Mad cow.

00:19.519 --> 00:21.646
Like I'll remember it. Mad cow. Mad cow.

00:21.730 --> 00:24.649
Love is an ugly business, my friend.
Ugly business.

00:25.025 --> 00:25.984
Ugly business.

00:37.537 --> 00:39.164
-It's ten o'clock.
-Are we not on?

00:39.247 --> 00:41.416
It's supposed to be Tuesday
at 10:00 every week.

00:42.000 --> 00:44.711
We've been moved.
We're Wednesday at 10:00.

00:44.794 --> 00:47.922
-Nobody called me.
-They told Howie in Word Processing.

00:48.006 --> 00:49.507
They called Howie in Word Processing?

00:49.591 --> 00:51.718
Are we Wednesdays at 10:00 from now on?

00:51.801 --> 00:54.554
No. We're off next week,
then on for the following two Wednesdays.

00:54.637 --> 00:57.599
-What about next year?
-Best to just keep checking in with Howie.

00:58.975 --> 01:01.561
Excuse me. Are you Denny Crane?

01:02.896 --> 01:05.648
Denny Crane. What can I do for you?
Let me rephrase.

01:06.441 --> 01:07.609
What can we do for each other?

01:08.068 --> 01:10.445
I'm Sunny Fields, of Sunny Fields Farms?

01:10.737 --> 01:13.323
-I'm in love.
-SUNNY (chuckles): You're cute.

01:13.656 --> 01:15.950
-That, too.
-You eat meat, Mr. Crane?

01:16.034 --> 01:18.578
-My place or yours?
-I'm a cattle rancher.

01:18.787 --> 01:21.039
The FDA is about to sign off
on cloned meat.

01:21.122 --> 01:23.208
Once they do,
the floodgates are gonna open.

01:23.291 --> 01:24.751
I need a lawyer to stop that flood.

01:25.502 --> 01:27.170
Are you that lawyer, Denny Crane?

01:27.545 --> 01:31.007
There's never been a dam or a damsel
I couldn't plug.

01:33.009 --> 01:34.260
Marry me.

01:37.680 --> 01:41.184
(theme music playing)

02:06.876 --> 02:09.212
I'm confused. Are you cloning the meat?

02:09.379 --> 02:12.507
No, no, sweetheart. The biotech companies
are cloning the meat.

02:12.590 --> 02:13.925
I'm the one that's trying to stop it.

02:14.008 --> 02:17.345
I believe that procreation should happen
the old-fashioned way.

02:17.428 --> 02:18.680
When can we get started?

02:19.013 --> 02:23.476
How far are we away from cloned animals
actually being a reality?

02:23.560 --> 02:25.812
Oh, hell, honey. They're already here.

02:26.187 --> 02:27.647
They have hundreds of pigs

02:27.730 --> 02:29.607
and some of their piglets
have already made it

02:29.691 --> 02:33.027
into the food supply, by the way,
and now, they're trying to use beef.

02:33.111 --> 02:37.115
My question is, who put the mad cows
in charge of the asylum?

02:37.198 --> 02:38.199
Hear, hear. Be nice.

02:38.658 --> 02:42.245
They have a moratorium on using cloned
animals which is about to be lifted.

02:42.328 --> 02:44.122
That's why I would like to move fast.

02:44.205 --> 02:47.584
-Denny, you don't need me on this.
-Carl. Carl.

02:50.920 --> 02:54.215
-Carl, uh, I need a heavy hitter.
-I thought you were a heavy hitter.

02:54.299 --> 02:57.385
I am. But I'd like to do my hitting
on her. I'm in love with her.

02:57.468 --> 02:59.304
Look, Carl, this is
a great opportunity for you

02:59.387 --> 03:01.222
to be a consumer advocate here,

03:01.306 --> 03:05.143
which the country needs because Nader
is running for president again.

03:05.226 --> 03:08.646
And, uh, well, I'd ask Alan,
but he's busy.

03:10.106 --> 03:10.940
Please?

03:18.031 --> 03:19.157
I'm just gonna say this,

03:19.240 --> 03:22.410
uh, and let me preface it by admitting
I know this is a crazy notion.

03:22.493 --> 03:24.621
-Okay.
-I wanna sue my nephew.

03:25.580 --> 03:26.623
Okay, what's he done?

03:26.706 --> 03:29.709
It's not what he's done so much
as what he's planning to do.

03:31.002 --> 03:32.253
And what does he plan to do?

03:32.670 --> 03:33.755
Vote for Obama.

03:34.631 --> 03:36.591
I could be wrong,
but I believe he has that right,

03:36.674 --> 03:39.052
unless there's some fine print
in the PATRIOT Act--

03:39.135 --> 03:40.470
Alan, he is a delegate.

03:40.553 --> 03:42.472
He plans to vote for Obama
at the convention

03:42.555 --> 03:46.309
even though his congressional district
voted for Clinton, as did Massachusetts.

03:46.601 --> 03:48.228
-Well, can he do that?
-Well, yes.

03:48.311 --> 03:50.647
That's the dirty little secret
no one's talking about.

03:51.064 --> 03:53.858
Even the pledge delegates can ignore
their constituencies.

03:53.942 --> 03:56.236
Uh, it's unethical, in my opinion.

03:56.319 --> 03:59.072
And if the rules allow for that,
then the rules have to be challenged.

03:59.155 --> 04:01.282
And by challenged,
you mean the little-used act

04:01.366 --> 04:03.117
of anarchy known as suing the nephew?

04:03.534 --> 04:07.538
Alan, this nomination could very well
come down to a handful of delegates,

04:08.164 --> 04:10.041
poached delegates, I might add.

04:10.124 --> 04:14.629
Every vote counts,
including my nephew's. Sue.

04:27.141 --> 04:28.726
I'm really quite shocked, Aunt Shirley.

04:29.060 --> 04:32.438
I've been taken completely unaware.
How can you sue me?

04:32.522 --> 04:33.648
-Mitchell--
-Mitchy.

04:35.316 --> 04:38.194
Mitchy, you don't think it's wrong

04:38.278 --> 04:40.321
that your entire district voted
for Hillary, but--

04:40.405 --> 04:44.951
Forty-two percent. It's funny how
a plurality can morph into an entirety.

04:46.035 --> 04:47.370
Must be that Clinton math.

04:48.329 --> 04:52.834
I think your aunt's point, Mitchy,
is that Hillary won your district

04:52.917 --> 04:55.837
as well as the entire state
of Massachusetts.

04:55.920 --> 04:57.797
You have a duty
to represent your constituency

04:57.880 --> 04:59.424
at the convention, do you not?

04:59.632 --> 05:01.926
Well, I'm not duty bound, Mr. Shore.

05:02.635 --> 05:05.471
Delegates are more like duty-urged.

05:06.472 --> 05:11.102
Mitchy, you're 22 years old,
with less voting experience than--

05:11.185 --> 05:14.564
(cell phone ringing)

05:14.647 --> 05:18.776
I'll say this for her. She is a bulldog.
Excuse me for a second.

05:20.611 --> 05:23.281
Probably calling to say
she found her voice again. (giggles)

05:26.075 --> 05:28.244
You have got to be able to stop him.

05:28.328 --> 05:32.332
(chuckles) I don't see how.
As he says, he's within party rules.

05:32.415 --> 05:35.209
-I can't bear it.
-Well, there's only two other options.

05:36.377 --> 05:38.796
We could stuff him in a barrel
and send him out to sea.

05:40.173 --> 05:42.842
-Or?
-We could sue the Democratic Party.

05:49.265 --> 05:52.143
You can't sue food or drugs.

05:52.560 --> 05:55.104
How can anybody sue food or drugs?

05:55.188 --> 05:57.690
We're suing the Food
and Drug Administration, Your Honor.

05:57.774 --> 05:59.901
-The FDA.
-What the hell is that?

05:59.984 --> 06:02.403
That would be the agency
in charge of your meds, Judge.

06:02.862 --> 06:06.199
And in fact, I would suspect somebody
very much like yourself or Denny

06:06.282 --> 06:08.493
-is in charge of that department.
-Objection.

06:08.576 --> 06:12.121
Mr. Sack, flattery has no place in this...

06:13.873 --> 06:15.166
It would be a courtroom, Your Honor.

06:15.500 --> 06:17.168
Your Honor, this should be
in federal court.

06:17.251 --> 06:18.628
They are suing a federal agency.
Jurisdiction--

06:18.711 --> 06:21.422
Next, he's gonna play the sovereign
immunity card. It's a dodge.

06:21.506 --> 06:23.091
Stop with the jibber-jabber.

06:23.508 --> 06:26.594
Jibber-jabber has no place
in my courtroom.

06:26.677 --> 06:28.388
You understand, Mr. Sack?

06:28.471 --> 06:30.139
Yes, Your Honor.
Jibber-jabber and flattery.

06:30.223 --> 06:32.100
May I call a witness to lay out my case?

06:32.183 --> 06:36.396
Silence. I will decide how to proceed.
I am the decider.

06:38.231 --> 06:39.107
Call a witness.

06:40.650 --> 06:43.361
Thank you, Your Honor.
I call Sunny Fields.

06:47.824 --> 06:53.121
How are we doing today, Judge?
Well, aren't you adorable up close.

07:04.298 --> 07:06.426
The motion is filed.
We're in at two o'clock.

07:08.302 --> 07:10.179
We're actually suing the DNC.

07:10.263 --> 07:13.766
Yes. I also subpoenaed Mitchy.
We'll need him as a witness.

07:14.851 --> 07:17.228
You realize the media will pounce on this.

07:18.604 --> 07:20.731
I've practiced law for 38 years

07:20.815 --> 07:23.818
and never once have I done
something stupid.

07:23.901 --> 07:27.029
Well, now you're being hard on yourself.
I've seen you be stupid many times.

07:27.113 --> 07:28.281
(chuckles)

07:31.200 --> 07:35.830
I sit here
in my tastefully decorated office

07:35.913 --> 07:39.834
and watch you go about tilting
at windmills.

07:40.710 --> 07:42.462
Many times beating the windmill.

07:44.088 --> 07:45.131
Well, it's my turn.

07:47.258 --> 07:51.804
It's my turn to stand up
and make a complete idiot of myself

07:51.888 --> 07:57.310
and do something that leaves this nation

07:57.393 --> 07:59.103
a slightly better place.

08:01.481 --> 08:03.774
That, and a chance to paste
your annoying nephew.

08:05.067 --> 08:07.862
Yeah. I can't pass that up.

08:09.572 --> 08:12.492
It's settled then.
We're off to sue the Democrats.

08:19.957 --> 08:21.209
I know the science, darling.

08:21.292 --> 08:24.670
I also know that most of the scientists
who did the testing we're hired

08:24.754 --> 08:26.422
by the cloning companies.

08:26.631 --> 08:28.841
The science on this is in the bag.

08:29.550 --> 08:31.552
A lot of people have no problem
eating cloned meat.

08:31.636 --> 08:34.222
Well, most people aren't even gonna know.
That's the worst part.

08:34.805 --> 08:38.309
The FDA doesn't even require
that the cloned stuff be labeled.

08:38.392 --> 08:39.977
I don't think I'd wanna know.

08:43.481 --> 08:46.317
Have you any evidence
that cloned meat is unsafe?

08:46.609 --> 08:48.945
Oh, it's too early to tell either way.

08:49.028 --> 08:53.324
But if it's not natural, would you eat it?

08:56.077 --> 08:58.079
All the FDA studies have concluded
that it's safe.

08:58.412 --> 09:01.624
Honey, the FDA said
that VIOXX was safe.

09:01.958 --> 09:04.293
Isn't the real issue here
that you're a cattle rancher

09:04.585 --> 09:05.962
and you don't want the competition?

09:06.045 --> 09:08.089
No, I'm more concerned
about animal abuse, darling.

09:08.506 --> 09:09.715
-Animal abuse?
-SUNNY: Yes.

09:09.799 --> 09:13.261
The surrogate mothers are pumped up
with high levels of hormones.

09:13.594 --> 09:16.597
The clones are often born
with compromised immune systems

09:16.973 --> 09:19.976
which require massive doses
of antibiotics,

09:20.059 --> 09:22.311
which, by the way, opens up the door

09:22.395 --> 09:25.523
for the veterinary pharmaceuticals
to enter into the human food supply.

09:25.606 --> 09:28.609
There is no evidence
that cloned meat poses any health risk.

09:28.693 --> 09:32.113
Darling, cloning increases the risk
of food-borne illness.

09:32.196 --> 09:34.365
Even the National Academy
of Sciences says so.

09:34.782 --> 09:38.369
Once you take nature out of the process,
which cloning does,

09:38.953 --> 09:42.206
it destroys the natural barriers
against disease.

09:42.290 --> 09:45.751
Now, that poses a health problem
for cows and people.

09:47.378 --> 09:48.588
Like you and me.

10:03.978 --> 10:04.937
(elevator bell dings)

10:05.021 --> 10:07.732
Mr. Shore, Wolfgang Blitzkrieg with the
best political news team in television.

10:07.815 --> 10:09.150
I have no comment yet.

10:09.233 --> 10:12.111
Ms. Schmidt, Wolfgang Blitzkrieg with the
best political news team in television.

10:12.194 --> 10:13.613
Could I get you to talk just for a second

10:13.696 --> 10:14.947
with the best political news team
in television?

10:15.031 --> 10:15.990
Go away.

10:16.073 --> 10:17.950
(overlapping dialog)

10:18.034 --> 10:19.201
This has been Wolfgang Blitzkrieg

10:19.285 --> 10:21.412
with the best political news team
in television.

10:21.495 --> 10:22.705
You only got it here.

10:23.914 --> 10:26.375
This is outrageous.

10:26.459 --> 10:29.503
We had a feeling you'd say that, Judge,
but we actually do have a case.

10:29.587 --> 10:30.838
No, you do not.

10:30.921 --> 10:33.257
The Democratic Party
is a private organization.

10:33.341 --> 10:35.092
We make what rules we want.

10:35.176 --> 10:36.761
Not when it violates one man, one vote.

10:36.844 --> 10:38.554
What is it you're asking me to do?

10:38.638 --> 10:40.097
We'd like a court order, Judge, that says

10:40.181 --> 10:43.017
that pledge delegates have to vote
for the candidate they're pledged to,

10:43.100 --> 10:44.769
certainly on the first ballot.

10:44.852 --> 10:47.271
You want me to tell the Democrats
how to run their own party?

10:47.355 --> 10:49.190
-Somebody's got to.
-(gavel thuds)

10:50.232 --> 10:53.486
Give me one good reason
why I shouldn't dismiss this right now.

10:53.569 --> 10:57.323
Okay, you're a fair
and open-minded jurist.

10:57.406 --> 10:59.367
-(gavel thuds)
-Give me another reason!

10:59.992 --> 11:03.454
Okay. As long as there are only
two political parties,

11:03.537 --> 11:05.581
the public only has two choices
for president.

11:05.873 --> 11:08.918
One of them is being picked by delegates
like Mitchy Weston,

11:09.001 --> 11:10.294
that toddler over there,

11:10.378 --> 11:15.007
whose vote is worth 13,000 times
the vote of you and me.

11:15.091 --> 11:16.509
You're talking about a process
that's been in effect--

11:16.592 --> 11:18.678
I know what process I'm talking about.

11:19.136 --> 11:21.472
And it's about time it be exposed
for the fraud it is.

11:21.555 --> 11:23.099
-Fraud?
-Yes, fraud.

11:23.182 --> 11:26.268
If the primaries really don't count,
then they are just a sham.

11:26.352 --> 11:29.814
They count! They're just not binding,
snidey butt.

11:32.149 --> 11:34.944
I want it on the record
that I've just been called "snidey butt"

11:35.027 --> 11:38.447
by a person whose vote
is worth 13,000 times

11:38.531 --> 11:41.158
more than mine, and yours,
and Your Honor's.

11:41.242 --> 11:42.993
That's enough!

11:43.452 --> 11:44.954
We'll adjourn until nine o'clock
tomorrow morning.

11:45.788 --> 11:48.165
I'll conduct a full evidentiary hearing.

11:48.249 --> 11:49.291
(reporters clamoring)

11:49.375 --> 11:50.501
Okay, Shirley, you're up.

11:50.751 --> 11:53.963
Ms. Schmidt, Wolfgang Blitzkrieg with the
best political news team in television.

11:54.046 --> 11:55.506
We really are the best, by the way.

11:55.589 --> 11:58.342
Can you tell me,
has this case been politicized?

12:06.267 --> 12:08.811
Oh, you were brilliant.

12:08.894 --> 12:12.898
-(chuckles) Honey, I'm always brilliant.
-No.

12:15.609 --> 12:18.195
I don't just jump into bed
with any woman, you know.

12:19.613 --> 12:23.159
Actually, I do.
But this time, it's different.

12:25.161 --> 12:25.995
I...

12:27.913 --> 12:29.415
I think we should be together.

12:29.915 --> 12:31.876
Mm. You're sweet.

12:31.959 --> 12:33.002
No, I mean it.

12:34.879 --> 12:36.255
I'm falling in love with you.

12:37.840 --> 12:39.925
Honey, I think you're cute as a button,

12:40.718 --> 12:43.012
but I tend to treat men like horses.

12:43.387 --> 12:46.223
-I ride 'em hard and then I turn 'em out.
-I'm okay with that.

12:50.019 --> 12:52.104
(sighs) Truth is, my...

12:53.564 --> 12:57.026
tawdry affairs tend to last longer
than my committed relationships.

12:57.902 --> 13:00.738
But this is different.

13:04.200 --> 13:06.869
I feel a... a real connection.

13:08.454 --> 13:10.247
Denny Crane, I'm a cattle rancher.

13:10.831 --> 13:14.835
You think a big city slicker like yourself
would be happy living on a farm?

13:17.046 --> 13:18.172
I love horses.

13:18.798 --> 13:21.258
I love cows. I love sheep.

13:23.219 --> 13:24.887
Especially sheep.

13:24.970 --> 13:26.555
SUNNY:
I'm an all-or-nothing kind of girl.

13:27.264 --> 13:30.643
If you're with me, you gotta be on a farm.

13:31.936 --> 13:32.770
I'm there.

13:35.439 --> 13:36.857
You're out of your mind.

13:36.941 --> 13:41.070
Oh, this woman, Alan.
She's the one. I know it.

13:41.153 --> 13:42.613
-In just one day?
-In ten minutes.

13:42.696 --> 13:44.573
-(chuckles) Oh, come on.
-DENNY: It's like a movie.

13:44.657 --> 13:46.283
A glance here, a look there.

13:47.701 --> 13:49.912
(sighs) Has that ever happened to you?

13:50.287 --> 13:52.331
-No.
-She's a goddess, Alan.

13:53.582 --> 13:56.335
You really are smitten.

13:58.504 --> 14:00.923
So is she. I could see it in her eyes.

14:06.262 --> 14:07.763
Did you know that I am as cute
as a button?

14:08.264 --> 14:14.103
Denny, I say this with love
and in the spirit of friendship.

14:15.062 --> 14:19.358
-The idea of you on a ranch--
-What?

14:20.442 --> 14:22.403
-Well, you're a little...
-A little what?

14:24.280 --> 14:26.907
Roly-poly. In a good way.

14:26.991 --> 14:28.242
I'm a rugged man!

14:28.325 --> 14:30.327
Yes. And cute as a button.

14:33.455 --> 14:34.498
Oh, dear.

14:37.960 --> 14:41.589
<i>With the best political news team</i>
<i>ever assembled in the history--</i>

14:56.395 --> 14:59.356
The rules may technically allow
the pledge delegates

14:59.440 --> 15:01.150
to ignore the mandate of the popular vote,

15:01.233 --> 15:03.694
but that's certainly not
what the Democratic Party advertises.

15:04.236 --> 15:06.906
People go to the primary polls
under the assumption,

15:07.531 --> 15:09.700
an assumption cultivated by the DNC,

15:09.783 --> 15:15.039
that whatever candidate wins that primary,
he or she will get the delegates.

15:15.539 --> 15:17.458
Let's put our cards on the table,
Miss Schmidt.

15:17.541 --> 15:19.543
-You're for Hillary?
-I am.

15:19.877 --> 15:21.921
And you want your nephew
to vote for Hillary?

15:22.713 --> 15:25.633
I want the delegates,
especially the pledge delegates,

15:25.716 --> 15:28.510
to give the primary some meaning.

15:28.928 --> 15:32.264
It should probably also be said
we're in a time of war.

15:34.183 --> 15:36.894
-What do you mean?
-Well, the country needs stability.

15:36.977 --> 15:40.314
It needs to count on its bedrocks,
its established traditions.

15:40.397 --> 15:43.984
For 20 years now, we've only had
two families in the White House.

15:44.068 --> 15:48.280
Just the two. First a Bush,
then a Clinton, then, uh, Clinton again,

15:48.364 --> 15:50.366
then another Bush, then that Bush again.

15:50.449 --> 15:51.492
It's time for another Clinton!

15:51.575 --> 15:56.205
We simply cannot afford to experiment
in such uncertain times.

15:58.582 --> 16:00.542
-What the hell was that about?
-What?

16:01.043 --> 16:02.586
You totally politicized this.

16:02.670 --> 16:04.713
You practically stumped for Obama!

16:04.797 --> 16:05.756
I did no such thing.

16:05.839 --> 16:09.802
I just happen to be a big fan
of dynasties and monarchies.

16:09.885 --> 16:11.136
Oh, I love monarchies.

16:11.220 --> 16:13.806
This is not to be turned
into your political forum, Alan.

16:13.889 --> 16:16.308
Look, Shirley, may I speak to you
for a second as a friend,

16:16.392 --> 16:19.311
one who can hold you in the bad days
and spoon you in the good ones?

16:19.395 --> 16:21.397
-Alan--
-This is a good thing for you,

16:21.689 --> 16:23.148
-what's going on here.
-How so?

16:23.232 --> 16:26.318
Well, you want Hillary, right?
Consider Hillary's behind in the count.

16:26.652 --> 16:28.195
She can't possibly be the nominee

16:28.487 --> 16:30.990
unless she poaches
some of Obama's pledge delegates.

16:31.073 --> 16:33.409
And if delegates are bound
to the mandate of the voters,

16:33.701 --> 16:36.745
that may be good for democracy,
but it would be very bad for Hillary.

16:36.829 --> 16:39.206
So you need to just chill out, relax.

16:39.289 --> 16:43.335
If anybody's gonna hijack this thing,
it's gonna be the Clintons. So just chill.

16:43.419 --> 16:45.671
If you even think of using this case
to plug Obama--

